 offer a path to middle-class security, so although marriage is not her first choice, Mathilde applies her shrewd understanding of class mores to pursue it - with results both triumphant and catastrophic.The last among Fontane's powerfully drawn female protagonists, Mathilde is unlike any previous heroine of a German novel: intelligent and energetic but plain and deeply pragmatic. We follow the fearless but flawed Mathilde from the bustling metropolis of Berlin to Woldenstein, a sleepy backwater town she single-handedly transforms, and back. Unknown in the English-speaking world, this compact work has the humor and pathos familiar to readers of Fontane, and is powerfully evocative of the politics of class, gender, and religion in late 19th-century Germany. An introduction, afterword, and extensive endnotes richly contextualize the work for both general readers and students of literature, history, gender studies, and German studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aGerman History. 4aGerman Literature. 4aModern History. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aGerman Realism.  aNaturalism.  aPoetic Realism.  aambition.  adiscrimination.  adomesticity.  aeducation.  ainterior monologue.  airony.  alaw.  amobility.  amodernization.  apoverty.  aprejudice.  apropriety.  arealism.1 aChambers, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuener, Rachael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311142849940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781805431152?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781805431152423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781805431152/original  a978-3-11-14